p.value: Identification of item, date; RG-030: Poly Archives Serial Publications Collection; box number, folder number; Poly Archives & Special Collections at Bern Dibner Library of Science and Technology.

The serial publications in this collection were loosely grouped together in the archives in the mid 2000s. Historical notes at the series level provide an explanation of each publication in this collection.

The publications in this collection include newsletters, bulletins, newspapers, department news, yearbooks, alumni magazines and literary journals. Collectively, these publications produced by Polytechnic students, faculty, alumni, and the administration, cover over 100 years of research, innovation, and campus life.

Fusion was a student newspaper owned and published by Polytechnic University. Fusion's office was on the Farmingdale campus and the paper was distributed to both Long Island and Brooklyn campuses. All Poly students were invited to submit articles for publication through the Farmingdale Student Life office or to become a member of the Fusion staff.

Fusion was re-inaugurated in 2004 as a magazine staffed by students of Polytechnic University and funded by the Department of Technical Communications. The new iteration of the magazine focused on engineering and technology articles as well as social issues important to engineering students and professionals.

The Polytechnic Engineer was a technical magazine, founded in 1898, for undergraduate students at Polytechnic. The publication lay dormant for forty years, when it was resurrected in 1960 with a new volume 1.

The Polytechnic News bulletin underwent slight title and audience changes over the years, but remained a widely distributed source of information about faculty research and happenings around Polytechnic. From 1955-1956 the bulletins were titled "Report from Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn." In 1957, the headline changed to "News from Polytechnic: A newsletter for the faculty in staff." In 1970, this title was tweaked to "The Polytechnic Faculty News: For faculty and staff of the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn." In 1974, the title changed to "Polytechnic News: A Newsletter of Polytechnic Institute of New York," which indicated both the university's name change and, no longer specifying faculty as the only audience, a wider distribution. In 1984 the title became "Poly News: Polytechnic Institute of New York - Newsletter - Brooklyn - Long island - Westchester." Finally, in 1986, reflecting yet another name change to the university, the title changed to "Poly News: Polytechnic University - Newsletter - Brooklyn - Long island - Westchester."

 Arrangement note

The series is arranged chronologically, with all name variations grouped together under the general series title "Polytechnic News." Bound volumes follow loose issues in boxes and folders.
